  { text: "The naturally occurring catecholamine in the body includes all but:", options: ["Dopamine", "Adrenalin", "Nor – Epinephrine", "Vasopressin"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Vasopressin is a hormone from the pituitary, not an adrenergic catecholamine like dopamine, adrenaline, or norepinephrine." },
  { text: "Which client would the nurse suspect of having a mitral valve prolapse?", options: ["60-year-old with CHF", "23-year-old male with Marfan’s syndrome", "80-year-old with AFib", "33-year-old with Down syndrome"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Connective tissue weakness in Marfan's syndrome often leads to mitral valve prolapse." },
  { text: "Spider angioma in the anterior abdominal wall of a patient with liver cirrhosis is due to:", options: ["Hepatic portal obstruction", "Portal hypertension", "Neovascularization", "Hyperventilation"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Note: Following provided user key. (Medically, these are usually linked to estrogen metabolism dysfunction)." },
  { text: "In Freud’s theory of personality____________:", options: ["The ego obeys the reality principle", "The id operates by secondary thinking", "Superego obeys pleasure", "Ego operates primary process"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "The ego operates on the reality principle to mediate id impulses with external logic." },
  { text: "Dizygotic twins:", options: ["Are genetically identical", "Come from a single fertilized egg", "May be of the same or different sex", "Are not really twins"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Fraternal twins formed from two separate eggs; can be same or opposite sex." },
  { text: "Cerebrospinal fluid is secreted by the:", options: ["Choroid plexus", "Astrocyte", "Microglial cell", "Oligodendrocyte"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Produced by the specialized choroid plexus in brain ventricles." },
  { text: "Movement of fluid from vascular system into peritoneal space excludes which factor?", options: ["Sodium retention", "Increased volume", "Increased lymph flow", "Increased hepatic synthesis of albumin"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Albumin increases oncotic pressure, keeping fluid inside the blood vessels; synthesis prevents ascites." },
  { text: "Arterial supply and venous drainage of the GI system including liver/spleen is termed ________ circulation:", options: ["Abdominal", "Para – renal", "Peritoneal", "Splanchnic"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Refers to the blood supply of the abdominal viscera." },
  { text: "Hemodynamic consequences of portal hypertension include all EXCEPT:", options: ["Ascites", "Varices", "Spider angioma", "Portal – systemic encephalopathy"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Note: Following provided answer key." },
  { text: "An example of displacement is:", options: ["Escape reality", "Ignoring reality", "Resisting demands", "Pent-up emotions directed to others than the source"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Defense mechanism involving transferring feelings from one target to a less threatening one." },
  { text: "Which of the following is NOT an antipsychotic drug?", options: ["Modecate", "Akineton", "Haloperidol", "Mellaril"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Akineton (Biperiden) is an anticholinergic used to treat motor side effects (EPS)." },
  { text: "The incubation period of measles is:", options: ["3-7 days", "5-7 days", "7-14 days", "14-21 days"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Standard viral period is typically 10-14 days." },
  { text: "During expiration, the volume of the thorax__________ as the diaphragm _______:", options: ["Decreases/contracts", "Decreases/relaxes", "Increases/contracts", "Increases/relaxes"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Note: Following provided user key. (Anatomically, expiration decreases volume)." },
  { text: "Hemorrhoid symptoms and discomfort can be relieved by the following EXCEPT:", options: ["High fiber diet", "Increased fluid", "Hydrophilic bulk agents (psyllium)", "Sitz baths"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Note: Following provided answer key." },
  { text: "Mechanical causes of intestinal obstruction include all EXCEPT:", options: ["Intussusception", "Tumors", "Stenosis", "Paralytic ileus"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Paralytic ileus is a functional failure of motility, not a physical mechanical blockage." },
  { text: "Which of these symptoms is closely associated with pulmonary tuberculosis?", options: ["Night sweat", "Restlessness", "Dark green sputum", "Skin discolouration"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Hallmark systemic sign of chronic infection in TB." },
  { text: "Primary hormone responsible for maintaining changes in the uterus during pregnancy:", options: ["Estrogen", "Progesterone", "hCG", "Prolactin"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Necessary to sustain the decidua and prevent uterine irritability." },
  { text: "Function of the decidua in the pregnant uterus:", options: ["Produces fluid", "Fetal nourishment", "Forms maternal portion of placenta", "Umbilical support"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Specialized uterine lining that anchors the placenta." },
  { text: "Effacement during pregnancy refers to:", options: ["Widening", "Shortening and thinning of the cervix", "Softening", "Rupture"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Cervical ripening process for labor." },
  { text: "Role of progesterone in uterine changes during pregnancy:", options: ["Stimulates contractions", "Promotes effacement", "Maintains endometrial lining", "Inhibits growth"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Progesterone prevents the breakdown of the decidua/lining." },
  { text: "Contribution to the initiation and progression of uterine contractions:", options: ["Decrease oxytocin", "Increase progesterone", "Surge in oxytocin and prostaglandin levels", "Decrease estrogen"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Oxytocin and prostaglandins stimulate regular uterine activity." },
  { text: "Role of prostaglandins in the first stage of labor:", options: ["Inhibiting contractions", "Softening and ripening the cervix", "Maintaining lining", "Relaxing muscles"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Chemical mediators used clinically to prepare the cervix." },
  { text: "Process of the fetal head descending into the pelvis:", options: ["Crowning", "Engagement", "Effacement", "Descent"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Entry of the fetal presenting part into the pelvic inlet (Station 0)." },
  { text: "Role of the Ferguson reflex in the first stage of labor:", options: ["Triggers oxytocin", "Stimulates descent", "Promotes dilation through positive feedback", "Inhibits contractions"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Mechanical stretch of the cervix stimulates further uterine activity." },
  { text: "Typical duration of the latent phase of the first stage of labor:", options: ["< 1 hour", "1-3 hours", "4-6 hours", "7-10 hours"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Early phase where cervix thins and starts to open." },
  { text: "In the context of abortion, what does 'selective reduction' refer to?", options: ["Method choice", "Reducing number of fetuses in multiple pregnancy", "Risk reduction", "Genetic selection"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Procedure to reduce multifetal pregnancies to a safer number." },
  { text: "All are CORRECT, EXCEPT, Pregnancy is associated with:", options: ["Increase cardiac output", "Increase venous return", "Increase peripheral resistance", "Increase pulse rate"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Pregnancy typically causes systemic vasodilation, decreasing peripheral resistance." },
  { text: "True statement regarding normal pregnancy:", options: ["Estradiol principal", "BP increases in 1st/2nd", "Tidal volume reduced", "Amniotic fluid mostly fetal urine (2nd half)"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Fetal swallowing and voiding are the primary regulators of fluid volume in later pregnancy." },
  { text: "Uterine contraction pattern typical during first stage of labor:", options: ["Irregular", "Prolonged", "Strong and coordinated", "Weak/infrequent"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "True labor contractions are coordinated and efficient." },
  { text: "Function of the amniotic sac during first stage of labor:", options: ["Cushion fetus", "Protect against infections", "Regulate temp", "Release prostaglandins"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "The intact sac acts as a physical barrier against ascending infection." },
  { text: "NOT a primary factor in determining fetal presentation:", options: ["Fetal attitude", "Fetal heart rate", "Fetal lie", "Fetal position"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Heart rate monitors fetal status but does not determine mechanics of position." },
  { text: "Presenting part in LOA and ROA positions:", options: ["Olecranon", "Chin", "Occiput", "Buttocks"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "The occipital bone is the reference point for cephalic vertex positions." },
  { text: "Correct order of cardinal movements of labor:", options: ["Flexion first", "Descent, flexion, internal rotation, extension, external rotation, expulsion", "Descent, internal rotation", "Descent, extension"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Standard mechanism used by the fetus to navigate the birth canal." },
  { text: "Woman should receive 500-1000ml of which solution before epidural?", options: ["Normal saline", "D5W", "D5W in LR", "Lactated Ringer solution"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Preloads volume to prevent the common side effect of post-anesthetic hypotension." },
  { text: "Uncommon fetal attitude resulting in a brow presentation:", options: ["Partial extension", "Complete extension", "Moderate flexion", "Complete flexion"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Brow presentation occurs when the head is partially extended rather than flexed." },
  { text: "Recommended WHO antenatal care model visits:", options: ["4 visits", "8 visits", "12 visits", "16 visits"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "The WHO 2016 model recommends a minimum of 8 contacts." },
  { text: "Screening test during ANC to detect chromosomal abnormalities:", options: ["Amniocentesis", "CVS", "Non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT)", "Glucose tolerance"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "NIPT uses maternal blood to check for fetal aneuploidy." },
  { text: "Primary function of theory in nursing:", options: ["Confuse practice", "To organize knowledge and explain phenomena", "Limit inquiry", "Discourage EBP"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Theory provides a systematic framework to classify and use data." },
  { text: "Distinguishes theory in nursing from other fields:", options: ["Lack of view", "No concepts", "A unique focus for knowledge development", "No EBP"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Nursing theories focus specifically on the human response to health and environment." },
  { text: "A theory in nursing allows for:", options: ["Random actions", "Limit prediction", "Relationship, proposals and predictions", "Ignoring actions"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Scientific theories provide logical links for future health outcomes." },
  { text: "Type of nursing theory applicable to a broad range of situations:", options: ["Narrow", "Borrowed", "Practiced", "Grand Theory"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Broad frameworks like Orem or Roy provide global perspectives." },
  { text: "Primary characteristic of Practiced Theory in nursing:", options: ["Chaos", "Limited applicability", "Academic only", "Guiding nursing actions in a specific setting"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Action-oriented guidelines for very specific clinical scenarios." },
  { text: "Nursing theory extending beyond practice, incorporating elements from other disciplines:", options: ["Narrow", "Borrowed", "Chaos", "Grand Theory"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Grand theories represent the highest level of multi-disciplinary integration." },
  { text: "Theory more likely to be applied in academic and research settings:", options: ["Practiced", "Borrowed", "Grand Theory", "Chaos"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Provides the foundational concepts and hypotheses for nursing science." },

  // Paper IV Batch 151-180 (Management, Ethics, Clinical)
  { text: "In which healthcare service are mental health assessments, counseling, and therapy provided?", options: ["Mental health care", "Primary care", "Secondary care", "Tertiary care"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Specialized service dedicated to behavioral and psychological well-being." },
  { text: "What type of healthcare service involves end-of-life care and support for terminal illnesses?", options: ["Hospice care", "Primary care", "Tertiary care", "Palliative care"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Hospice focus is comfort and dignity during the final stages of life." },
  { text: "Principle suggesting a clear and unbroken line of communication from top to bottom:", options: ["Unity of command", "Unity of direction", "Scalar chain", "Equity"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Fayol's principle defining the formal hierarchy of authority and communication." },
  { text: "Nurse forgot morning Lasix; client develops pulmonary edema. Potential legal charge:", options: ["Assault", "Slander", "Negligence", "Tort"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Failure to perform an expected duty (medication administration) that leads to patient harm." },
  { text: "Involuntary commitment of a threatening client is an example of:", options: ["Fidelity", "Veracity", "Autonomy", "Beneficence"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Acting in the best interest of the patient's safety and the safety of others." },
  { text: "Leadership style where staff feel disorganized and have no direction:", options: ["Autocratic", "Bureaucratic", "Laissez-faire", "Authoritarian"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Laissez-faire (hands-off) leadership often leads to lack of guidance and frustration." },
  { text: "Best description of nurse’s responsibility concerning written consent (rape case):", options: ["Explain and sign", "Verify signed and attached to chart", "Tell MD patient agrees", "Verify family signed"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "The nurse verifies that the consent process was completed and documented properly." },
  { text: "Following initiation of epidural anesthesia, the nurse should give priority to:", options: ["Cervical dilation", "Placing client in supine position", "Checking blood pressure", "Fetal heart rate"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Note: Following user-provided key. (Clinically, BP is the standard priority assessment)." },
  { text: "Which client has the highest risk for bacteraemia?", options: ["PICC line", "Central venous catheter (CVC)", "Implanted port", "Peripheral IV"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Direct access to large vessels and high infection rates make CVCs the highest risk." },
  { text: "Color bag used to dispose of offensive/hygiene waste:", options: ["Orange", "Yellow", "Yellow and black stripe", "Black"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Standard color coding for non-infectious but offensive waste." },
  { text: "Action for suspected anaphylaxis (short of breath, wheezy, red patches):", options: ["Call help/O2", "O2/Salbutamol", "O2, Adrenaline 500mcg IM, Salbutamol, call help", "Adrenaline only"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Multimodal emergency response including the gold-standard treatment (Epinephrine)." },
  { text: "Management of moderate malnutrition in children:", options: ["Supplementary nutrition", "Hospitalization", "Weekly assessment", "Document intake for three days"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Initial step involves detailed assessment of current dietary patterns." },
  { text: "Observation frequency during blood transfusion:", options: ["Temp/Pulse start/end", "Before, 15 min, guidelines, end of bag", "Urinalysis included", "Hourly only"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Close monitoring in the first 15 minutes is critical for early detection of reactions." },
  { text: "What is comprehensive nursing assessment?", options: ["Foundation for control", "In-depth health status/exam on admission", "Assessment of specific risk", "Continuous monitoring"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "The baseline detailed evaluation performed at entry to care." },
  { text: "Professional responsibilities of qualified nurse in medicines management:", options: ["Timely admin", "Safe handling and ensuring patient understanding", "Knowledge of names", "Liaison with pharmacy"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Nurses are responsible for the entire safety cycle including patient education." },
  { text: "Newly qualified nurse action if patient vomits immediately after tablets:", options: ["Prescribe different", "Check for tablets, document, discuss alternative route", "Pre-medicate antiemetics", "Hide in food"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Assessment of medication retention is required before deciding on re-administration." },
  { text: "Health teaching for client with Gout:", options: ["Increase fluid 2-3L/day", "Sunshine", "Avoid paracetamol", "Avoid dairy"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Hydration helps promote uric acid excretion by the kidneys." },
  { text: "Incorrect statement regarding CHF and pitting edema:", options: ["Water pill helps", "Lasix helps", "Furosemide/Digoxin combined", "Lasix increases blood pressure"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Furosemide is a diuretic; it typically decreases blood pressure by reducing volume." },
  { text: "Signs of opioid toxicity EXCEPT:", options: ["CNS depression", "Miosis", "Cyanosis", "Tachycardia"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Opioid overdose typically causes bradycardia, not tachycardia." },
  { text: "Reason the intravenous route would be used for medications:", options: ["Refusal of tablets", "Cost effective", "Reduces infection", "Immediate therapeutic effect and precise control"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "IV allows for rapid onset and titration of dose." },
  { text: "Dehydration concern: true of someone said to be in positive fluid balance?", options: ["Output exceeds input", "Increase IV rate", "Stop chart", "Input has exceeded output"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Positive balance means the body has retained more fluid than it lost." },
  { text: "Pharmocokinetics can be described as:", options: ["Effects on systems", "Absorption/Distribution/Metabolism/Excretion (ADME)", "Mechanism of action", "Drug-drug reaction"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Defines the movement of the drug through the body ('What the body does to the drug')." },
  { text: "CVA patient with dysphagia. What should NOT be an intervention?", options: ["Sitting upright", "Water/Clear liquids", "Instruct patient to use a straw", "Review swallow ability"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Using a straw increases the risk of aspiration by delivering fluid too quickly." },
  { text: "Correct detail regarding cardiopulmonary resuscitation:", options: ["5-6cm deep at 100-120/min", "2:15 ratio", "Lower third sternum", "Check breath 1 min"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Standard 2020 AHA/ERC guidelines for high-quality chest compressions." },
  { text: "Most common cause of autonomic dysreflexia in SCI patients:", options: ["Bowel obstruction", "Fracture", "Pressure sore", "Urinary obstruction"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Bladder distension is the most frequent trigger for this hypertensive crisis." },
  { text: "Looking after 75yo woman 2 days post-hysterectomy. Reduce DVT risk:", options: ["Regular analgesia", "Verify stockings removed daily", "Stockings/hourly limb exercise", "Analgesia, mobilize, LMWH, stockings"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Combination of pharmacological prophylaxis, mechanical support, and early mobility." },
  { text: "Preferred position for abdominal Paracentesis:", options: ["Supine head slightly elevated", "Supine knees bent", "Prone", "Side-lying"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Allows gravity to pool fluid in the lower abdomen for easier drainage." },
  { text: "Etiology behind shock after lumbar puncture:", options: ["Increased ICP", "Headache", "Medication side effect", "CSF leakage"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Loss of CSF volume can lead to intracranial hypotension and neurological symptoms." },
  { text: "Acute leukemia evaluation: most important inquiry by the nurse:", options: ["Sleeping habits", "Respiratory infection in last 6 months", "Weight loss", "Alertness"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Frequent or persistent infections are a hallmark sign of white blood cell dysfunction." },
  { text: "Loss of intellect, balance, prions positive. Possible disease:", options: ["Gastroenteritis", "Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease", "HIV", "Urgent bowel"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "CJD is a rare, fatal brain disorder caused by prion proteins." },

  // Paper IV Batch 181-250 (Med-Surg, Stats, Clinical)
  { text: "21yo male engaged Hodgkin’s senior. Priority diagnosis:", options: ["Sexual dysfunction related to radiation", "Anticipatory grieving", "Tissue integrity", "Fatigue"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "At this developmental stage (Erikson's Intimacy), reproductive health is a primary concern." },
  { text: "Determine response to treatment in autoimmune thrombocytopenic purpura:", options: ["Platelet count", "WBC count", "Potassium", "PTT"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "ITP is a disorder where the body destroys its own platelets." },
  { text: "Teaching for ATP client with platelet count 80,000:", options: ["Bleeding precautions", "Falls", "Oxygen", "Energy"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Counts below 100,000 increase risk for spontaneous bleeding." },
  { text: "Addison’s disease client receiving IV glucocorticoids. Implementation:", options: ["Glucometer readings", "Intake/output", "Sodium/Potassium", "Daily weights"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Steroids can significantly elevate blood glucose levels." },
  { text: "Positive Kernig’s sign description:", options: ["Pain on flexion of hip and knee", "Nuchal rigidity", "Head turn pain", "Dizziness"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Stretching the inflamed meninges during leg extension causes intense pain." },
  { text: "Post-laryngectomy client nonresponsive/pale, BP 90/40. Initial action:", options: ["Trendelenburg", "Increase saline infusion", "IV Atropine", "Emergency cart"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Note: User key B. (Addressing potential hypovolemic shock)." },
  { text: "Warfarin therapy Protime 120 seconds. Plan of care inclusion:", options: ["Assess for signs of abnormal bleeding", "Increase dose", "Instruct drug therapy", "Neuro assessments"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "A Protime of 120s is extremely elevated and carries a high hemorrhage risk." },
  { text: "Ranitidine (Zantac) for erosive gastritis. Administration:", options: ["30 minutes before meals", "With each meal", "Bedtime single dose", "60 minutes after meals"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Pre-meal dosing provides maximal acid suppression during eating." },
  { text: "Deformity location for Heberden’s nodes in osteoarthritis:", options: ["Men only", "Distal interphalangeal joint", "Proximal", "Dorsolateral"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Specific to the terminal finger joints." },
  { text: "Main difference between RA and OA:", options: ["Gender specific", "OA localized, RA systemic", "OA systemic, RA localized", "Dislocations"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "OA is degenerative wear-and-tear; RA is an autoimmune inflammatory process." },
  { text: "True statement about using a cane:", options: ["Walker better", "Affected side", "Unaffected side", "Ambulate without"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "The cane is held on the strong side to provide better balance for the weak side." },
  { text: "Medication to administer to a client with gout:", options: ["Aspirin", "Furosemide", "Colchicines", "Calcium gluconate"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Colchicine is specific for reducing uric acid crystal inflammation." },
  { text: "Wet-to-dry dressing for diabetic foot ulcer rationale:", options: ["Contain exudate", "Mechanical trauma", "Debride the wound", "Prevent discomfort"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Removing the dried gauze pulls away necrotic tissue (mechanical debridement)." },
  { text: "Acute Addisonian crisis expected laboratory finding:", options: ["Hyperkalemia", "Reduced BUN", "Hypernatremia", "Hyperglycemia"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Lack of aldosterone leads to potassium retention and sodium loss." },
  { text: "Appropriate nursing intervention for SIADH:", options: ["Infuse IV rapidly", "Increased oral intake", "Restricting fluids", "Glucose containing IV"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Fluid overload with low sodium (dilutional) is the primary problem in SIADH." },
  { text: "Effectiveness check for 3-month effort controlling Type 2 DM:", options: ["Urine glucose", "Fasting glucose", "Serum fructosamine", "Glycosylated hemoglobin levels"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "HbA1c provides an average of glycemic control over roughly 90 days." },
  { text: "Substances produced by the adrenal cortex:", options: ["Glucocorticoids and androgen", "Catecholamine", "Mineralocorticoids/Catecholamines", "Norepinephrine"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "The cortex produces steroid hormones; the medulla produces catecholamines." },
  { text: "Lab test elevated in smokers, not a general indicator of cancer:", options: ["Acid phosphate", "Serum calcitonin", "Alkaline phosphate", "Carcinoembryonic antigen level"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "CEA is often used to monitor treatment but can be baseline-high in smokers." },
  { text: "Assessment findings characteristic of iron deficiency anemia:", options: ["Night sweat", "Dyspnea, tachycardia and pallor", "Nausea", "Itching"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Classic symptoms of decreased oxygen-carrying capacity." },
  { text: "HIV positive pregnancy teaching needs more correction when client says:", options: ["Placenta viral transfer", "Birth control", "Not every birth is HIV positive", "I will need a C-section if I become pregnant"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Note: User key D. (Modern HIV management often allows for vaginal delivery if viral load is undetectable)." },
  { text: "AIDS discharge instruction at home:", options: ["Disposable gloves bath", "Boiling utensils", "Avoid sharing toothbrushes and razors", "Avoid serving dishes"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Prevents potential blood-borne transmission." },
  { text: "Purpose of CBC before surgery:", options: ["Hepatic dysfunction", "Urine constituents", "Abnormally low hematocrit and hemoglobin levels", "Electrolyte imbalance"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Ensures the patient is not anemic before potential surgical blood loss." },
  { text: "Newly admitted dietary history: common allergen identification:", options: ["Bread", "Carrots", "Orange", "Strawberries"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Berries are frequently associated with histamine reactions." },
  { text: "Peritoneal dialysis preparation first action:", options: ["Bruit/Thrill assessment", "Warm the dialysate solution", "Position on left side", "Foley insertion"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Cold fluid causes abdominal cramping and discomfort." },
  { text: "Elderly risk of sensory deprivation reason:", options: ["Medication sensitivity", "Decreased visual auditory and gustatory abilities", "Surroundings", "Musculoskeletal"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Natural age-related decline in sensory organ function." },
  { text: "Emphysema client becomes restless and confused next step:", options: ["Pursed-lip breathing", "Temperature", "Potassium", "Increase O2"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Encourages CO2 expiration and provides a focusing task." },
  { text: "Immediate objective for client with ureteral colic and hematuria:", options: ["Pain decrease", "Weight", "Hematuria", "Hypertension"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Colic pain is excruciating; relief is the priority." },
  { text: "Neurologic complications of multiple myeloma usually involve:", options: ["Brain", "Muscle spasm", "Renal dysfunction", "Myocardial irritability"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Note: Following user-provided key. (Clinically, hypercalcemia causes many neuro symptoms)." },
  { text: "Jose narcotic respiratory arrest arterial PaCO2 expected value:", options: ["15mmHg", "30mmHg", "40mmHg", "80mmHg"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Hypoventilation leads to severe CO2 retention (Hypercapnia)." },
  { text: "Hypertension drug reaction short of breath/tachypnea/decreased LOC:", options: ["Asthma", "PE", "Respiratory failure", "RA"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Severe acute impairment of gas exchange." },
  { text: "Cirrhosis increased risk for excessive bleeding reason:", options: ["Impaired clotting mechanism", "Varix", "Nutrition", "Trauma"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "The liver fails to synthesize essential clotting factors." },
  { text: "Term for reduced CO due to ineffective pumping:", options: ["Anaphylactic", "Cardiogenic shock", "Distributive", "MI"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Shock originating from primary heart muscle failure." },
  { text: "Factor causing high blood pressure to drop to normal:", options: ["Sodium excretion only", "Retention", "Kidneys’ excretion of sodium and water", "Retention/Excretion mix"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Reduces total intravascular volume." },
  { text: "Health economics concerned about all EXCEPT:", options: ["Costs", "Benefits", "Consequences", "Ensuring everyone has everything he wants"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Economics deals with scarcity; it is impossible for everyone to have everything." },
  { text: "Statement not absolutely correct about health economics:", options: ["Wants", "Improve pocket well-being", "Love/Recognition", "Material unlimited"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "The goal is societal resource efficiency, not individual pocket-lining." },
  { text: "Wants of man multiplying factors EXCEPT:", options: ["New products", "Economic Production change", "Economic development no negative impact", "Consumption change"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Economic growth often introduces new environmental and health risks." },
  { text: "CVD and Cancer commoner in developed countries due to:", options: ["Lifestyle", "Better economic", "Corruption", "Leadership"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Sedentary habits and high-calorie diets are prevalent in affluent nations." },
  { text: "Significant public health problem of developed countries:", options: ["Obesity", "Crime rate", "Affluence", "Power"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Linked to the 'Double Burden' of malnutrition and overnutrition." },
  { text: "Pre-requisite of developing countries breaking poverty cycle:", options: ["Fly abroad", "Substantially improved health outcomes", "Exchange rate", "Borrowing"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "A healthy workforce is essential for economic productivity." },
  { text: "Evaluates how well resources are used to achieve desired outcome:", options: ["Allocative efficiency", "Efficiency", "Technical Efficiency", "Resource efficiency"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Efficiency is the ratio of output to input." },
  { text: "Measures resource allocation to group that can benefit most:", options: ["Allocative efficiency", "Efficiency", "Technical Efficiency", "Resource efficiency"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Optimizes the mix of goods/services to maximize utility." },
  { text: "Extent to which resources are combined to achieve maximum outcome:", options: ["Allocative efficiency", "Efficiency", "Technical Efficiency", "Resource efficiency"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Focuses on producing a specific output at minimum cost." },
  { text: "Maximise benefits with limited amount of resources:", options: ["Cost production", "Cost analysis", "Cost benefits", "Cost effectiveness"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Compares relative costs and outcomes of different courses of action." },
  { text: "Measure of disease burden, quality and quantity of life:", options: ["Mortality", "Quality Adjusted Life Year (QALY)", "Morbidity", "Life span"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Used to quantify health outcomes for economic analysis." },
  { text: "Hypothetical years spent in perfect health comparable to actual:", options: ["Status index", "Health year equivalent", "QALY", "Life span"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Refines the QALY concept for specific health states." },
  { text: "Considered an economic good EXCEPT:", options: ["Cars/Food", "Thermometers", "Healthy state", "Prolonged hospitalisation"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Hospitalization is an expense or 'bad' rather than a desirable consumer good." },
  { text: "Rules governing how scarce resources satisfy wants:", options: ["Economic system", "Global economy", "Mixed economy", "Ethics"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "The framework for resource distribution." },
  { text: "Positioning for a client in hemorrhagic shock:", options: ["Flat with legs elevated", "Flat", "Trendelenburg", "Semi-sitting"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Promotes venous return to the core/heart." },
  { text: "Indwelling catheter purpose in trauma/conscious patient:", options: ["Measure urine flow indicator of shock", "Cast protection", "Comfort", "Prevention"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Kidney perfusion is a sensitive indicator of hemodynamic status." },
  { text: "Assess fluid status in incontinent CRF client:", options: ["Estimate", "Turgor", "Weigh the client daily", "Record voidings"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Weight changes are the most accurate reflection of fluid retention." },
  { text: "Subjective data recorded upon admission assessment:", options: ["Weight", "Red rash", "State 'My hands itch'", "Temperature"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Subjective data is what the patient says (Symptoms)." },
  { text: "Break in sterile technique observation:", options: ["Drops on field", "Waist height", "Flap away", "Saline splatters onto cloth backing"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Moisture allows 'wicking' of bacteria from the surface through the field." },
  { text: "Action to prevent vascular complications post-abdominal surgery:", options: ["Turn", "Deep breath", "Leg circles and toes circles every 2 hours", "Dangle"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Activates the calf muscle pump to prevent DVT." },
  { text: "Reddened coccyx skin not broken: pressure ulcer stage:", options: ["Pre-ulcer", "Stage I", "Stage II", "Stage III"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Non-blanchable erythema of intact skin." },
  { text: "Vomiting, now slow shallow breathing: acid-base imbalance:", options: ["Resp acidosis", "Resp alkalosis", "Metabolic alkalosis", "Metabolic acidosis"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Loss of gastric acid causes alkalosis; lungs compensate by retaining CO2." },
  { text: "Heparin readily available drug:", options: ["Vitamin K", "Caffeine", "Calcium gluconate", "Protamine sulfate"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Protamine is the specific antidote for heparin overdose." },
  { text: "Know nitroglycerin is effective when:", options: ["Tingling", "Pulse increase", "Pain subsides", "Activity tolerance"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "The primary indication for NTG is the relief of anginal pain." },
  { text: "Anginal pain during sexual intercourse: best response:", options: ["Ambivalent feelings", "Many persons have less pain when partner on top", "Well rested", "Cocktail"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Reduces cardiac workload and metabolic demand." },
  { text: "Left-sided congestive heart failure finding:", options: ["Neck veins", "Dyspnea", "Hepatomegaly", "Pitting edema"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Left failure causes pulmonary congestion (fluid in lungs)." },
  { text: "PVD ischemic ulcers on ankles goal:", options: ["Tolerance", "Anxiety", "Protect from injury", "Body image"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Prevents secondary infection and further tissue loss." },
  { text: "Chlorothiazide (Diuril) 500 mg instruction:", options: ["2 quarts liquid", "Hard cheese", "Drink orange juice or eat a banana daily", "No aspirin"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Thiazides are potassium-wasting diuretics; high-K foods are necessary." },
  { text: "Thrombophlebitis in the leg indicator:", options: ["Diminished pulse", "Color changes", "Red, shiny skin", "Coolness"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Indicates inflammation and congestion of the vessel." },
  { text: "Include in teaching plan for hypertension:", options: ["Reduce calcium", "Avoid aerobic", "Reduce alcohol intake", "Limit fluid"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Excessive alcohol increases blood pressure and interferes with meds." },
  { text: "Assessment indicating ferrous sulfate NOT taken as ordered:", options: ["Flushed cheeks", "Energy", "Nausea", "Stools are light brown"], correctAnswer: 3, rationale: "Iron typically turns stools dark green or black." },
  { text: "Child with leukemia bruises easily due to:", options: ["Fibrinogen", "Clotting elsewhere", "Decreased platelets", "Decreased erythrocytes"], correctAnswer: 2, rationale: "Malignant marrow infiltration suppresses megakaryocyte production." },
  { text: "Pernicious anemia signs and symptoms:", options: ["Bruising", "Beefy-red tongue", "Rash", "Pruritus"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Glossitis is a classic symptom of Vitamin B12 deficiency." },
  { text: "Best time to collect sputum for culture:", options: ["Morning right after awakening", "After breakfast", "2 hours after eating", "Bedtime"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Secretions pool in the lungs during sleep, maximizing specimen yield." },
  { text: "Greatest concern after thoracentesis:", options: ["Hemoptysis", "Respirations 28", "Pulse 80", "Temp 99F"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Coughing up blood indicates potential lung trauma or hemorrhage." },
  { text: "Bloody nose instruction:", options: ["Sit up tilt forward, grasp soft part", "Lie down tilt backward", "Sit up lean backward", "Lie down head lower"], correctAnswer: 0, rationale: "Prevents swallowing/aspirating blood while providing local pressure." },
  { text: "Tracheostomy performed priority:", options: ["Shave neck", "Establish a means of communication", "Insert Foley", "Start IV"], correctAnswer: 1, rationale: "Preparing the patient for the psychological and practical loss of verbal voice." }
